Response bias arises when respondents do not answer questions honestly or correctly for social motives, fear of retaliation, or other factors. Measurement error arises when the questions or scale used to assess attitudes are not adequately created or verified, resulting in erroneous or untrustworthy findings. Self-report bias arises when the individual supplying the attitude data is not the same person whose attitudes are being assessed, resulting in erroneous or untrustworthy findings. 